Mind, Self, and Society
Self - Actors reflect on themselves as objects; it is developed and is not initially there at birth.

Mind, Self, and Society
Self - Actors reflect on themselves as objects; it is developed and is not initially there at birth.
The self is composed of two parts, the “I” and the “Me”, both are a part of an individual’s self concept and the self is the dialogue between the two.

Mind, Self, and Society
Self - Actors reflect on themselves as objects; it is developed and is not initially there at birth.
The self is composed of two parts, the “I” and the “Me”, both are a part of an individual’s self concept and the self is the dialogue between the two.
“I” is spontaneous, unsocialized, unpredictable, and impulsive aspect of the self.  The subject of one’s actions.

The self is composed of two parts, the “I” and the “Me”, both are a part of an individual’s self concept and the self is the dialogue between the two.
